1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,200
Thanks for joining. Today we're talking about how to actually evaluate a
retrieval-augmented generation system once you've built one.

2
00:00:05,200 --> 00:00:11,800
Most teams start by eyeballing a handful of answers, which catches the
obvious failures but misses everything else.

3
00:00:11,800 --> 00:00:18,400
The first thing to separate is retrieval quality from generation quality.
These fail independently and need different fixes.

4
00:00:18,400 --> 00:00:25,000
For retrieval, the standard metrics are recall at k and mean reciprocal
rank, measured against a labeled set of query to relevant passage pairs.

5
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:31,600
If recall at k is low, no amount of prompt engineering on the generation
side will fix the system, because the evidence was never retrieved.

6
00:00:31,600 --> 00:00:38,200
For generation, we care about groundedness, whether every claim in the
answer is actually supported by the retrieved passages.

7
00:00:38,200 --> 00:00:45,000
An answer can be fluent and confident and still be ungrounded if the model
fills a gap in the retrieved evidence with something from its own training.

8
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:51,400
A practical way to check groundedness at scale is to use a second model as
a judge, scoring correctness, completeness, and clarity separately.

9
00:00:51,400 --> 00:00:58,000
The judge should always be shown the same evidence the generator was
shown, otherwise you're grading against the judge's own knowledge instead.

10
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:04,600
We've also found it useful to log every tool call the system makes, not
just the final answer, because that's what makes failures debuggable.

11
00:01:04,600 --> 00:01:11,200
When a run fails, you want to see which sub-queries were issued, what came
back, and where the answer diverged from the evidence.

12
00:01:11,200 --> 00:01:17,800
One limitation worth naming: automated judges tend to be lenient on
completeness and stricter on correctness, so track them separately.

13
00:01:17,800 --> 00:01:24,000
Running the same fixed question set after every prompt change is what
turns this from vibes into an actual regression test.

14
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:28,000
That's the core loop. Happy to take questions.
